MELTING POTES

Task A : SDM-NEO Data analysis
Author

Amélie Lehuen

Published

January 1, 2022

1 Dataset description for M&M

All data treatment has been conducted with R version 4.2.2 (2022-10-31 ucrt) except for MARS3D pre-treatment on Matlab 2019a. Significance levels are tagged for p < .0001 with “****”, p < .001 with “***”, p < .01 with “**”, p < .05 with “*”.

1.1 Areas map

The Seine estuary has been studied regarding several historically known areas that have either habitat or communities differences. These areas are mainly mudflats and subtidal areas, are represented in Figure 1.

1.2 Biologic dataset

The raw data (n= 50,948) has been harmonised and grouped to obtain a single database of 31,079 observations, and 187 sampling stations in total (with some variation in coordinates from year to year), with an average of 87 stations per campaign, occurred mainly in the months of Oct, Sep, Nov. Along the all period covered by the dataset, from 2000 to 2019, discarding before 2000 (too few observations n=216), with 1 to 2 sampling campaigns per year, a series of 5-years periods has been defined, 2000-2005 the building of ‘Port 2000’ with high disruption in the estuary area; 2006-2010; 2011-2015; 2016-2019. 627 different species has been founded, and C. edule counts 543 observations. Focus for following treatment is made on mudflats only for their biologic relevance for C. edule (Cote Fleurie (n= 1), North Downstream Mudflat (n= 82), North Median Mudflat (n= 198), North Upstream Mudflat (n= 2), Octeville (n= 3), OffShore (n= 39), South Mudflat (n= 218)).

1.3 Cerastoderma edule data structure

With a closer look on the data for C. edule, it is represented in Figure 2 the differences of biomass [gAFDW/m²] regarding periods and areas. The observations are split into periods as 2000-2005 (n= 108), 2006-2010 (n= 155), 2011-2015 (n= 174), 2015-2019 (n= 106). They are seldom in North Upstream Mudflat, where the water are more brackish.

1.4 Abiotic dataset

All Seine Bay MARS3D model is calculated in a grid of 78,400 mesh (700 by 112), focused on the Seine Estuary with a grid of ‘only’ 5,184 mesh (103 by 68), with the coordinates of Longitude -0.0361 to 0.3217 and Latitude 49.3382 to 49.5488. Mars mesh corresponding to the stations localisation in the biologic dataset are at total 157 with the distinction in the position in the tidal area as Infratidal (n= 48), Intertidal (n= 41), Subtidal (n= 93), Supratidal (n= 19).

All variables have been observed and a correlation study has been conducted to select the more pertinent factors and avoid autocorrelation between factors.

  • Mud content is chosen over Sediment total conc to link with other references (Corr = -0.77****).
  • Current Speed daily max is chosen over Current_Speed to reflect hydrodynamics occurring on mudflats (Corr = 0.73****).
  • Inundation time is chosen rather than True bathymetry, to be more informative on tidal position (Corr = 0.89****).
  • Salinity daily range is preferred to Salinity to emphasize more the tidal influence (Corr = -0.59****).
  • Temperature is picked upon Temperature daily range for its accessibility (Corr = -0.52****) and the range being reflected by the Inundation time (Corr = -0.75****).
  • Bed shear stress is preferred to MES mud to focus on erosion phenomena more than MTZ processes (Corr = 0.60****).
  • Bed shear stress is poorly correlated to Bed shear stress daily max (Corr = -0.06 ) but the latter is not kept for its difficulty to get that kind of measurement.
  • Yearly sediment budget is not correlated to any other variable but its distribution makes it not relevant.

Models are built with two abiotic factors to increase their reliability. The couples tested are:

  1. Current Speed daily max and Inundation time : to compare results with (Cozzoli et al. 2014), and these variables are easily retrieved with some high frequency measurement (COASTHF) . They have also a interest because they contains information on the position in the tidal area that could evolve with sea level rise and the hydrological conditions impact by the river flowrate change due to climate change even though they have a significant correlation (Corr = 0.56****)

  2. Mud content and Bed shear stress: Those variables are determinant in a building of an erosion model such as MARS3D (Corr = -0.10*).

  3. Temperature and Salinity daily range: These factors are easily measurable on high frequency also (Somlit). They are both bearing the climate change for the global temperature change and the evolution of the river regime that would impact the salinity profile of the estuary (Corr = 0.02 ).

  4. Temperature and Inundation time : (Corr = 0.52****).

The four couples of factors has been treated with the different ways of calculation : either linear with interaction, or non linear with bifactorial gaussian equation with the biomass as biologic response Figure 3.
